snippet.textDisplay: Fun side fact: that odd Fraunhofer institute's mp3 codec kind of defined how mp3 could sound while taking up noticeably less diskspace than contemporary options. It's been quite a big deal, considering having like 16/32(/64!)mb storage on your early mp3 player, and quality vs file size was a big concern (.wav audio ~10mb/min, 128kbit mp3 ~1+mb/min, optimized codec you could get down to ~700kb/min-ish iirc). I fondly remember using it generously for transcoding bloated 192kbit Napster downloads to "quite okay 96kbit", putting whole albums on my mp3 thingie (think mobile cassette tape players ["walkman"] for reference), before FH started to realize they could actually make money off of that IP :)

snippet.textDisplay: So long as I don't ever see an ad on premium, they can do what ever they want for ads for free viewers as far as I'm concerned. Ad blockers still work (mostly, Google is actively working to make things difficult for them) and with the antitrust investigations into Google's advertising platform going on only time will tell what will happen next. I honestly would not be surprised if Youtube eventually becomes one of those sites what won't let you in easily unless you white list it in your ad blocker or disable it.
